[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Catching up on a few things that have been on the to-do list today. We have a look at a videotovideo restylizer that solves actually a couple of problems that we\'ve had. Plus, we\'re going to swing over to Higsfield to check out their new character consistency feature'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and a few other things. All that plus a not creative AI image upscaler. Yeah, what\'s that all about? Well, we\'re going to find out. So, kicking off, I think you guys know that I am a big fan of videotovideo'

[00:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'restylization workflows. I\'ve been playing around with video to video really since the beginning of video to video when it was still like weird and warpy like this. Don\'t get me wrong, I still love this stuff. And of course, it'

[00:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'opens up the door to a lot of creativity when you start utilizing your own footage and bringing them into videotovideo workflows. And of course, as I have documented a number of times on the channel, you can take some of your jankier AI video outputs, run them'

[00:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'through a videotovideo process, and kind of, you know, save the day. That said, as always, it is AI. Nothing is ever perfect. Two kind of big problem spots that we commonly run into are stylization overloads, where, you know,'

[01:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'things tend to drift off into 3D animation territory, or, as I\'ve mentioned in a few previous videos, lip-sync. Lip sync always tends to be a bit of an issue, but we are getting pretty close in terms of that being'

[01:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'stamped out. Today, we\'re going to take a look at Mago\'s latest update and um yeah, I think currently at least they are definitely leading the pack there. So, let\'s check it out with our Once Upon a Time in the West test. &gt;&gt; Looks like we\'re shy of one horse.'

[01:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; You brought two too many. &gt;&gt; I mean, come on. How hard is Chuck Bronson with that line? Okay, let\'s take it over to Mago and give it a uh cyberpunk western styization. Looks like we\'re shy one horse.'

[01:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; You brought two too many. &gt;&gt; So yeah, that\'s looking pretty good. The way that this was accomplished was, of course, taking the first frame of each shot and bringing it through midjourney for a restylization pass. Of course, the big thing here to me was the lip sync.'

[01:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, naturally with Jack Elim\'s character in the restylization, he\'s wearing like a cybernetic mask. We don\'t get that, but we do get like sort of like that actor sway essentially the performance, and that\'s kind of what I really love about video to video. So,'

[02:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'hopping into Mago. And to note, this new version is still in beta, there is a link to the weight list down below. Secondly, while this might look a bit on the confusing side, it\'s actually pretty easy. Uh, let\'s run through it real'

[02:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'quick. So, starting off with a blank slate here, uh, I\'m just going to bring in this midjourney generated video. Uh, I love this one. Like the sneering king. Love this guy. Um, so we\'re just going to drag him in. Uh, and you\'ll note once it\'s loaded in, you\'ll note that we have'

[02:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'a bit of a timeline actually happening here. This is definitely a first that I have seen in a videotovideo restyle it. All you have to do from here is hit the little I guess like magic uh fairy dust button here. Um this will bring in our options. So taking that first frame,'

[02:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'bringing it back over to midjourney for a restylization. Uh we end up with a couple of different options. Uh all of which look pretty great. Uh you don\'t have to use midjourney obviously. You can use any image restylizer that you want. Uh say flux context as well. So'

[03:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'once we have the image that we want to use, we simply drag it up to here. So, this becomes our first frame. Uh, from there, uh, it will actually it auto prompts here for some reason. Um, that\'s probably a beta thing. Got to delete'

[03:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that. It does actually autoprompt for you here. So, you can just simply add that into the prompt. Um, you see here we have our style references. From here, you\'re going to want to move over to these other tabs. Under choose a model, there are a couple of different options.'

[03:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Obviously, we will be going with the V3 beta here. Mago is generating at 1280. So, the bonus here in using a midjourney video is that we\'re kind of getting a little bit of a sneaky upscale. Uh, you can turn on interpolation. We\'re going'

[03:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to move up next to the control nets settings. Here\'s where things get pretty interesting. Uh, we do have a couple of different options here, including depth, uh, normal map, pose, and soft edge. It defaults to depth. So, that\'s what we\'re'

[03:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'going to use for right now. Um, you can change the strength of that as well. But right here, face mesh. Um, if we enable that, that\'s where things get pretty interesting. shift is something that I have found uh I just turn up just a'

[04:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'little bit. Uh this helps with temporal consistency. Um lastly, and this is kind of the most interesting and important part is that um if we come up here, you\'ll notice that we have this range um here. So we can we can adjust the amount'

[04:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of um yeah the amount of video essentially that we are rendering at one time. Uh so as you can see down here um I have well I just finished that off. Uh, I just set it to uh 0 to 47 frames. And obviously that only renders this'

[04:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'section. So, um, let\'s take this all the way out and redo it. And there you go. Now we have the entirety of our clip, our evil king, looking even more evil than usual. Uh, now, why would you want to break them into separate clips? Well,'

[04:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'returning to our Once Upon a Time in the West clip, um, if we have a cut in our shot, uh, what ends up happening a lot of times is I\'ll go to this generation for example. um you\'ll run into this issue where this was our initial image'

